 @Blackquill_ it goes by per universe though Cassandra probably had a means by which she could simultaneously destroy every universe, especially since we see alternate Universe infinity stones retain their capabilities within the Void, and even has some level of effect on Multiversal Travel and Manipulation as seen by the Infinity Sling Ring and Infinity Ultron both being able to bridge the Gap between the Multiverse. 

I think the TVA is the only location where the Infinity Stones don’t have any power, but even Gods like Loki lack power in there too. It could be assumed that most magics and dimension + extradimensonial powers are null and void within TVA so as to manage threats like Celestials and Gods. Threats like Mutates, Mutants, and Inhumans are sure to retain their powers in some way, shape, or form. 

Question, would Captain America and other Super Soldiers classify as Mutates like Spiderman and Hulk, or would they have their own classification of Super Human because their powers are very rarely anything beyond just being Human+

 @lewdeaton7385  To be fair Madonna was without compare in the 80s, no-one could even touch her.
In 1986 (only 3 yrs into her first album) Madonna received the MTV Vanguard Award before Michael Jackson,
In 1989, she received the Artist of The Decade 1980s award (Mega Artist) elected by MTV, Billboard and DIY magazine.

 @Dioioego-x5q  Only a narrow minded person could willfully  miss the fact that Madonna pushed the envelope just like countless women before her! And this fact would have been relevant to her generation, so I know she grew up being influenced by these women! Joan Jett was fighting sexism in the punk genre before Madonna came on the scene. And Cher pushed the envelope way before Madonna's time. Cher bared her body in a time it was socially unacceptable to just have a hand print in your body suit, covering your nipples, bird and butt crack!

So don't act like Madonna was the first female in music to push the envelope, and fight for freedom! Though no one can take away the impact "like a prayer" had on the American public! And for that matter regular people all over the world! No one can take the meaning from her early works! She was amazing! But she had help, it wasn't her creativity alone. And that's where people misunderstand. She had a team behind her and she had many mentors who passed on their knowledge.

Instead of bashing Lady Gaga, I wish Madonna had mentored her, and helped her along in her musical journey. But she's like so many, her fame went to her head and now she's petty! She's not interested in anything outside herself and what affects her because she's self centered!

